SIMPLE: lustre
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lustre
<hw>Lus"tre</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>lustrum</ets>: cf. F. <ets>lustre</ets>.]</ety> <def>A period of
five years; a lustrum.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Both of us have closed the tenth <qex>luster</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Bolingbroke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lustre</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Luster</ent>⟦br⟧
<mhw>{

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Lustre
<hw>Lus"tre</hw>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[F. <ets>lustre</ets>; cf. It. <ets>lustro</ets>; both fr. L.
<ets>lustrare</ets> to purify, go about (like the priests at the lustral
sacrifice), traverse, survey, illuminate, fr. <ets>lustrum</ets> a
purificatory sacrifice; perh. akin to E. <ets>loose</ets>. But
<ets>lustrare</ets> to illuminate is perhaps a different word, and akin
to L. <ets>lucere</ets> to be light or clear, to shine. See
<er>Lucid</er>, and cf. <er>Illustrious</er>,
<er>Lustrum</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Brilliancy; splendor; brightness; glitter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The right mark and very true <qex>luster</qex> of the diamond.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir T. More.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The scorching sun was mounted high,⟦br⟧
In all its <qex>luster</qex>, to the noonday sky.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ There is a tendency to limit the use of
<xex>luster</xex>, in this sense, to the brightness of things which do
not shine with their own light, or at least do not blaze or glow with
heat. One speaks of the <xex>luster</xex> of a diamond, or of silk, or
even of the stars, but not often now of the <xex>luster</xex> of the
sun, a coal of fire, or the like.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Renown; splendor; distinction; glory.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His ancestors continued about four hundred years, rather without
obscurity than with any great <qex>luster</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir H.
Wotton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A candlestick, chandelier, girandole, or the like,
generally of an ornamental character.</def> <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>The appearance of the surface of a
mineral as affected by, or dependent upon, peculiarities of its
reflecting qualities.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The principal kinds of luster recognized are:
<xex>metallic</xex>, <xex>adamantine</xex>, <xex>vitreous</xex>,
<xex>resinous</xex>, <xex>greasy</xex>, <xex>pearly</xex>, and
<xex>silky</xex>. With respect to intensity, <xex>luster</xex> is
characterized as <xex>splendent</xex>, <xex>shining</xex>,
<xex>glistening</xex>, <xex>glimmering</xex>, and
<xex>dull</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A substance which imparts luster to a surface, as
graphite and some of the glazes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A fabric of wool and cotton with a lustrous surface,
-- used for women's dresses.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Luster ware</b></col>, <cd>earthenware decorated by
applying to the glazing metallic oxides, which acquire brilliancy in the
process of baking.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lustre</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Luster</ent>⟦br⟧
<mhw>{

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Lustre
<hw>Lus"tre</hw>, }</mhw> <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Lustred</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>;
<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Lustering</conjf>, <it>or</it>
<conjf>Lustring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To make lustrous.</def>
<mark>[R. & Poetic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Flooded and <qex>lustered</qex> with her loosened gold.</q>
<rj><qau>Lowell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lustering</ent>⟦br⟧

